        <txttip left="1056" top="186" right="1199" bottom="232" content="10.0.1.5&#x0D;&#x0A;255.255.255.0" fontname="Consolas" fontstyle="0" editsize="140" txtcolor="-16777216" txtbkcolor="-1" charset="1" />
        <txttip left="27" top="448" right="1354" bottom="734" content="Instructions:&#x0D;&#x0A;1. Configure the Name, IP Address and Subnet Mask of all the devices&#x0D;&#x0A;2. Test connectivity from each PC to every other PC&#x0D;&#x0A;3. Use th command &apos;display mac-address&apos; to check the MAC address tables of switches A and B. Take note of the mappings&#x0D;&#x0A;   of PC4, 5 and 6 to Switch A, and the mappings of PC1, 2 and 3 to Switch B?&#x0D;&#x0A;4. Check the arp cache of PC1, 2 and 5. Take note of the information in the arp cache.&#x0D;&#x0A;   (to check the arp cache, go to the PC command tab, and type &apos;arp -a&apos; without the quotes)&#x0D;&#x0A;5. Capture backets at Eth0/0/10 of Switch B. Note the kind(type) of exchanged information. Where is it from? where is it to?&#x0D;&#x0A;   What is it for?&#x0D;&#x0A;  Answer: Information will be from office A to Offce B, it is for testing connectivity  &#x0D;&#x0A;6. Save the complete work as &apos;FirstName-UserID-Lab3&apos;&#x0D;&#x0A;FFT: What would happen if the link between Switch A and B got a problem? How can we guard against this issue?&#x0D;&#x0A;  Answer: The connection from Office A to Office B will be cutted down and we can protect that through doing regular check up" fontname="Consolas" fontstyle="0" editsize="140" txtcolor="-16777216" txtbkcolor="-2044184" charset="1" />
    </txttips>
</topo>
